title: Realtime index task
body:
Indexing service realtime:
- Add SegmentAnnouncer, ServerView, QueryRunnerFactoryConglomerate to TaskToolbox
- Tasks can advertise ability to answer queries (through returning non-null from
  getQueryRunner)
- WorkerTaskMonitor (the thing on a worker that tracks running tasks) is now a
  QuerySegmentWalker
- LockAcquireAction is now blocking

Standalone realtime:
- MetadataUpdater now built from SegmentAnnouncer, SegmentPublisher instances.
- Sinks can take a version instead of always using interval.start. The realtime
  plumber selects a version using a VersioningPolicy.
- Plumbers gained a startJob method.
- Realtime plumbers gained an implementation for finishJob.

Assorted other changes:
- TaskAction.perform throws IOException
- TaskActions generally have better stringification
- Renamed TaskMonitor -> WorkerTaskMonitor
- Retry failed RemoteTaskActionClient submissions using a RetryPolicy

I added LinearShardingSpec under shard package and LinearPartitionChunk under partition package. This is a little different from SingleDimensionShardSpec. The problem is, in eu-west-1 AWS, the account of druid ec2 instance is different from the account managing s3 bucket. title: New balancer
body:
This pull request is to replace the size-based balancer/assigner with a new cost-based one.  The idea is that we want to discourage certain segments from being co-located on compute nodes.  Two big, recent, segments that belong to the same datasource should live on different compute nodes.

The new analyzer is the BalancerCostAnalyzer.  When balancing, it (pseudo-)randomly picks proposal segments to move.  For each proposal segment, it calculates the cost of co-locating it with other segments on all compute nodes.  Then it greedily moves the segment, decreasing the cost of the cluster.  Assignment is treated in a similar fashion.

title: Tiered Compute Nodes
body:
This commit introduces subtypes to Druid Servers (compute nodes). The idea behind subtypes is that the master can be configured to assign segments to a given subtype depending on a set of rules.

Rules are stored in a separate database table and contain information about the type of node a given segment should be assigned to or if the segment should be dropped. Each datasource requires its own set of rules. The rule table may also include a set of default rules. The master reads all rules from the table. Each time a request is made for the rules of a given datasource, the default rules will automatically be included. Additional information about rules and compute node tiers are available upon request.

This commit also removes the Druid Master Replicator Helper as it is no longer needed. The code has been refactored such that the Druid Master Assigner and Dropper helpers now take care of managing replication.

Finally, moar(!) unit tests because unit tests are awesome.

title: Some modifications on how to register things in Druid
body:
I think eventually Registererers will become the endpoint for plugins in Druid. Ideally I hope to be able to register an object like a complex metric or a query type and also register some information about how to serde the object. 

I deprecated BaseNode and renamed it to QueryableNode because I found it a bit confusing that many new nodes I was creating could not extend BaseNode (the name implies something a bit more extendable). QueryableNode implements RegisteringNode because I was thinking that we can create new Node interfaces and new concrete Node classes can extend those interfaces. This way common operations can be written that apply to all Nodes of a certain type.

title: Build and example fixes
body:
Here are a couple of minor fixes that were required for me to get the examples running on OS X 10.7.4 and Java 1.7.0_04-b21:
- 6a9d86e fixes a build issue by removing what appears to be an unused import.
- ae44e3e adds a wildcard jar to the classpath, similar to the twitter example.
- 9575326 updates .gitignore to ignore the output of the examples.

They are all minor changes that shouldn't have major repercussions, but I haven't tested these changes on other platforms or environments.
